HEADWORD: Disencumber
<hw>Dis`en*cum"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Disencumbered</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Disencumbering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>dis-</ets> +
<ets>encumber</ets>: cf. F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧sencombrer</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To free from encumbrance, or from anything which clogs, impedes, or
obstructs; to disburden.</def> <rj><au>Owen.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>disencumbered</qex> myself from rhyme.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Disencumbrance</ent>⟦br⟧
